\subsection{On the $p$-rational number fields}\label{section-p-rational}

A number field  ${\rm K}$ is called \emph{$p$-rational} if the Galois group ${\mathcal G}_{S_p}$ of the maximal pro-$p$-extension of ${\rm K}$ unramified outside $p$ is pro-$p$ free. From the extensive literature on  $p$-rational fields, we refer in particular to Jaulent-Nguyen Quang Do \cite{JN}, Movahhedi-Nguyen Quang Do  \cite{MN}, Movahhedi \cite{M}, and Gras-Jaulent\cite{GJ}.
A good general reference  is the book of Gras \cite{gras}.

\medskip

\begin{defi}
If ${\mathcal G}$ is a pro-$p$ group, let us denote by ${\mathcal T}({\mathcal G})$ the torsion of ${\mathcal G}^{{\mathrm{ab}}}$. 
When ${\mathcal G}={\mathcal G}_S$, put ${\mathcal T}_S:={\mathcal T}({\mathcal G}_S)$ ; when $S=S_p$, put ${\mathcal T}_p:={\mathcal T}_{S_p}$.
\end{defi}

A standard argument in pro-$p$ group theory shows the following:
\begin{prop}
A pro-$p$ group ${\mathcal G}$ is free if and only if ${\mathcal T}({\mathcal G})$ and  $H^2({\mathcal G},{\mathbb Q}_p/{\mathbb Z}_p)$ are trivial.
\end{prop}

